        "messageID": "msg_e1a299bed001Wp8mmkIjaFR6nC",
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Likely root cause: `rate_limiter.ts` probably does a check-then-schedule sequence around token expiry without an atomic/shared “refresh in progress” guard.\n\nA typical race would be:\n\n1. Request A checks token expiry and sees expired.\n2. Request B checks token expiry before A records any pending refresh state.\n3. Both proceed to schedule refresh work.\n4. The limiter now has duplicate refresh tasks for the same auth identity/token bucket.\n\nThe vulnerable shape is usually something like:\n\n```ts\nif (isExpired(token)) {\n  scheduleRefresh(token)\n}\n```\n\nor even:\n\n```ts\nif (isExpired(token) && !refreshScheduled) {\n  scheduleRefresh(token)\n  refreshScheduled = true\n}\n```\n\nif `refreshScheduled` is set too late, scoped per request, or not keyed correctly.\n\nThe fix is likely to make refresh scheduling single-flight per token/user/key: store a shared pending promise or in-flight marker before starting async work, then have concurrent callers reuse it. The important property is that the in-flight state is established synchronously before any `await`, timer callback, or external scheduling boundary.\n\nDo not edit yet.",
        "time": {
          "start": 1778555397854,
          "end": 1778555402677
        },
