      {
        "id": "prt_e1a29c5e40018dX8WHP6a1YFes",
        "sessionID": "ses_1e5d66425ffet7CcoRG6e96fq5",
        "messageID": "msg_e1a29bb7f002SyHG7FHVikUtZT",
        "type": "text",
        "text": "That failure mode is plausible if the mutex protects the wrong lifetime or key.\n\nA mutex only prevents duplicate refresh scheduling among code paths that share the same mutex object. If each request handler, controller instance, middleware instance, worker, or dependency-injected auth client gets its own mutex, then concurrent refresh requests for the same tenant can still run through separate locks.\n\nExample shape:\n\n```ts\nclass RateLimiter {\n  private refreshMutex = new Mutex()\n\n  async handleRefresh(req) {\n    await this.refreshMutex.runExclusive(async () => {\n      if (isExpired(req.token)) {\n        scheduleRefresh(req.tenantId)\n      }\n    })\n  }\n}\n```\n\nThis only works if all requests for a given tenant hit the same `RateLimiter` instance. It can fail if:\n\n1. A new handler/rate limiter instance is constructed per request.\n2. The service runs multiple Node workers/processes/pods, each with its own in-memory mutex.\n3. Dependency injection scopes the limiter as transient or request-scoped instead of singleton.\n4. The mutex is global rather than tenant-keyed, causing over-serialization across unrelated tenants.\n5. The expiry state and the mutex live in different scopes, so the lock does not actually cover the shared token state.\n6. The critical section releases before durable in-flight refresh state is recorded.\n\nThe over-serialization concern is also real: a single global mutex would make unrelated tenants wait behind each other. The safer design is usually tenant-keyed single-flight: maintain a shared `Map<tenantId, Promise<RefreshResult>>` or explicit in-flight marker, set synchronously before async refresh begins, and have concurrent requests for the same tenant await/reuse that work.",
        "time": {
